# Scalability — landing (~1M users)

The landing must handle **high traffic spikes** (campaigns, beta invites) with minimal Firestore cost per visitor.

## Traffic profile

- Most visitors: **zero Firestore reads** — static Flutter Web assets from Hosting CDN.
- One write per successful waitlist signup — design for **1M+ waitlist docs** over time (admin lists paginate in `four_drinking_admin`).

## Firestore usage (hard rules)

- **No** Firestore listeners on the landing — use one-shot `add()` on submit only.
- **No** unauthenticated reads from landing (waitlist is admin-read-only in rules).
- Do not add features that poll Firestore on page load or scroll.
- Keep waitlist documents small; avoid large blobs or unbounded metadata maps.

## Waitlist writes

- Use `FieldValue.serverTimestamp()` for `createdAt` (required by rules).
- Do not dedupe client-side only — if duplicate emails matter, handle in admin/Functions later; do not add expensive pre-read queries from public client unless rules allow and scale is justified.

## Assets & build

- Optimize images/SVGs for Web; lazy-load gallery if it grows.
- Keep `main.dart.js` lean — landing should stay a thin shell.

## Cross-repo impact

- Waitlist growth triggers `sendWaitlistWelcomeEmail` (admin Functions) — new fields must not break the trigger.
- Index needs for admin waitlist UI belong in `four_drinking_admin/firestore.indexes.json`.

## Definition of done (scale)

- [ ] No new Firestore reads on page load
- [ ] Writes are single-doc creates, bounded payload size
- [ ] Admin repo informed if waitlist schema or volume assumptions change
- [ ] Rough note: writes per conversion (target: 1 write per signup)
